    <h2>Pizza oven failure during service hours &mdash; we treat it as the emergency it is</h2>
    <div class="body-text">
      <p>Commercial pizza ovens in Los Angeles &mdash; from Neapolitan deck ovens in Silver Lake to Lincoln conveyor lines in Hollywood delivery operations &mdash; are the production heart of the kitchen. A thermostat that won&rsquo;t hold 550&deg;F, a conveyor belt motor that seized mid-rush, or a gas valve failure before Friday dinner service is a revenue emergency.</p>
      <p>We diagnose first. The $120 commercial diagnostic covers the full assessment: temperature verification, gas system check (for gas units), mechanical inspection, and control system evaluation. After diagnosis you get two numbers: labor and the specific OEM part. You approve before we start. Gas pizza oven calls include supply pressure verification and post-repair leak test at no extra charge. Temperature is verified at set point before we leave.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tip-block">
      <div class="tip-lbl">&#9733; Temperature calibration &mdash; the most misdiagnosed pizza oven issue</div>
      <p>A deck oven that &ldquo;doesn&rsquo;t get hot enough&rdquo; is most commonly a thermostat calibration issue, not a failed heating component. Thermostat drift is common after years of high-temperature cycling. Calibration requires no replacement part &mdash; just accurate thermometer verification and adjustment. We test calibration before recommending any component replacement. On a gas deck oven, this can be the difference between a $240 labor call and a $400+ gas valve replacement.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
